Yeah, as you'd mentioned, I would have this as another entity in the ``values.js`` file.  Just have it do this same calculation, but cache it like:

    if (_.isUndefined(platformArray)) {
        platformArray = _.map(thPlatformMap, function(val, idx) { return idx; });
    }
    return platformArray;

That way it only does that work once.

we'll need a release note saying that IE11 is not supported.  I'm totally fine with that.  Edge isn't perfect, but IE must die.  However, I'll be the one getting complaints about it not working if it's not totally clear.  In fact I'd be fine with adding:

```
try {
    Promise;
} catch {
    alert("Sorry, OSMD is not supported in Internet Explorer or other pre-ES6 browsers");
}
```

Apologies for missing to review this. In general, it's better to use a ticker than to sleep. That's because, when exiting, you really should not leave goroutines running. So I would re-write this block as:

```
// HACK (bacongobbler): poll etcd for changes in the log drain value
// etcd's .Watch() implementation is broken when you use TTLs
//
// https://github.com/coreos/etcd/issues/2679
go func() {
  t := time.NewTicker(time.Duration(publishInterval))
  for {
    select {
      case <-exitChan:
        return
      case <-t.C:
        resp, err := client.Get(publishPath+"/drain", false, false)
        if err != nil {
          log.Printf("warning: could not retrieve drain URI from etcd: %v\n", err)
          continue
        }
        if resp != nil && resp.Node != nil {
          drainChan <- resp.Node.Value
        }
    }
  }
}()
```

